The Ode has been severely criticised, and certainly not only are the three first stanzas commonplace, but the contrast between their formal and official frigidity and the licentious vigour of the rest of the Ode is very harsh. For the war with Spain see 2. 6. 2 n.

1. Herculis. Hercules is one of Horace's stock types of virtue ultimately deified (cf. 3. 3. 9), but he was also specially connected with Spain as having brought away the oxen of Geryon, and the worship of him as Hercules Victor (cf. victor) at the Ara Maxima was popular with the lower orders, cf. o plebs. Moreover in Β. c. 24 plebs Romana had received from the emperor a donative of 400 sesterces apiece ; Mon. Anc. 3. 10. 2. morte, ‘to have sought the laurels death alone can buy.’ He had been seriously ill at Tarraco and rumours (cf. dictus) of his death had probably reached Rome.
